Validation using SIRIUS

The SIRIUS file is loaded all its molecular formula are used and matched against all molecular formula that have been determined by the network propagation algorithm. If there is any match, the entry will be yes, if there is none it will be no. If there is no molecular formula available, either in SIRIUS nor in the annotated species, the entry will be NA.

The first plot shows all matches including NAs, whereas the second plot removed the NAs, in order to better evaluate the matching annotations. The second plot provides the information of the percentage of features that have a matching and a miss-matching molecular formula (number of NA are not considered.)

ggplot(data = df_s, aes(x = network_layer, y = Freq, fill = siriusMatch)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 0.7, position = "stack") +
  geom_text(aes(label = perc), position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size = 3.2) +
  labs(title = "No of Annotations") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#69005f", "#ff506e", "black")) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = pretty_breaks(n = 12)) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 1))

ggplot(data = df_s[!is.na(df_s$siriusMatch), ] %>% group_by(network_layer) %>% 
  mutate(perc = paste0((round(Freq / sum(Freq) * 100, 1)), " %")), 
  aes(x = network_layer, y = Freq, fill = siriusMatch)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 0.7, position = "stack") +
  geom_text(aes(label = perc), position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size = 3.2) +
  labs(title = "No of Annotations") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#69005f", "#ff506e", "black")) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = pretty_breaks(n = 12)) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 1))

Glucose annotations

The annotation of Glucose variants of GPNAEs is mainly accomplished by propagation in die mass-difference layer because the MS2 spectra are too different. Therefore, this section evaluates the properties of the Glucose annotations of this dataset. First, we want to create a sub-network and keep glucose annotations only.

annoGluc <- results_top[results_top$network_annotation %like% "C6H10O5", ]

Evaluation of benefits of Homol Series

We test if we see any benefits/ better annotation by features that are somehow connected in the homologous series network, because they are more likely to be real biological features because of the RT trends. Therefore we create a sub network, where we remove all features that show no connection in the homologous series layer.

# remove nodes that have no homol series (from original file)
homol_net <- net_df[!is.na(net_df$HSIDs), ]

#get cluster_ID of the nodes that appear on homol series layer
homols <- unique(c(homol_net$from, homol_net$to))

# filter results file by those features appearing in homol series
results_homol <- results_top[results_top$Row %in% homols, ]

Validation using manually Annotated nodes

In order to verify how good annotations are with the network propagation algorithm, we next create a sub network were we only keep nodes where we have an manual annotation (i.e.a molecular formula for matching). With that we can first validate how good our annotations are and secondly, validate if filtering nodes for the homologous series increases our annotation success or if we just lose important annotations.

#how many does match
